UV–vis spectra (Fig. 1
                        (c)) displayed absorbance peaks at 344 nm and 234 nm, attributed to the π-π* transitions of CC and CN bonds, and the n-π* transition of CO or CN bonds in N-CQDs [10], respectively. Interestingly, no significant differences were observed among dopant contents, indicating minimal impact within a certain range. Fluorescent spectra (Fig. 1
                        (d-f)) showed emission wavelengths (λ
                           em
                        ) at 432 nm across excitation wavelengths (λ
                           ex
                        ) from 280 nm to 380 nm, demonstrating excitation-independent photoluminescence. Compared to QY of N-CQDs synthesized from CA/urea in literature [11–13], N-CQDs0.8 demonstrated a relatively high QY (Table 1
                        ), consistent with elevated CN and CO groups. These groups likely enhance charge transfer processes, boosting fluorescence QY. N-CQDs0.8, optimized in composition, was selected for further investigation.
